t4487.text: And this story is just the tip of the iceberg on the stories I have with my ex-husband.

t4488.text: He was so hungover that he was still vomiting for days after when we left to go to Sweden (my ex-husband is Swedish). And finally when he did stop being angry; he just could not grasp why what he had done wrong and why I was so upset with him.

t4489.text: In his sleep. He then spent the better half of the next day glaring at me because he had a horrid hangover and I still made him come to the lunch my grandparents were throwing for the family. This was all overseas in Poland.

t4490.text: And that he was damn lucky to have a fiancé like me, who is also a nurse (we weren’t married yet). Instead he became cranky and angry at me because I kept waking him up to take sips of fluids and made him sleep side lying so he wouldn’t choke on his vomit in case he vomited

t4491.text: This was a 24 year old man... I was damn lucky my Uncle helped me haul him up two flights of stairs because there was no elevator. Did his parents help me? No. Did I ever get a thank you from my ex husband? Nope. Not until my then best friend pointed out he could of died...

t4492.text: I got him undressed and into the shower because he was covered in vomit and got him into bed. Mind you this was a 183cm, approximately 90kg man I was supporting when I’m only 156cm myself... in other words I’m tiny compared to my ex.

t4493.text: I routinely check his breathing every half an hour; ran out to a nearby petrol station to buy sports drinks to ensure he got electrolytes and fluid into him and I almost got ran over because there were no pedestrian pathways on the roads surrounding the hotel.
